post_text: The Strafford R-VI School District has some exciting news for our parents! We've been notified we will receive funding from the USDA to provide free breakfast and lunch to ALL of our preschool-12th grade students beginning September 10. The program ends December 23, 2020 or until funds are depleted. When second semester begins in January, lunch and breakfast expenses return to normal. If your student has a credit on his or her account, this will be applied to second semester. If you have any questions, please contact Vicki Barnum at 736-7000 ext. 1452.

post_text:
We can't wait to see you Monday! Here are some reminders:
* Don't forget a facial covering...these are required for all bus riding students and 5th-12th grade students while at school. Students PK-4th grade are strongly encouraged to wear a facial covering.
* Don't forget a pre-filled water bottle labeled with your student's name. There will be limited availability of water fountains, but bottle fillers are available districtwide.
* Take a first day photo at home. Parents cannot walk students to the doors. Watch Monday morning for a Facebook post about sharing these photos!
* We know this school year is different than the normal but we are so excited to see you!

post_text: New student registration will be held Monday, August 3-Friday August 21 in our central office board room from 9:00am-3:00pm each day. This will be for all Strafford Schools new students entering preschool-12th grade. Parents will need to bring proof of residency (examples include water bill, electric bill, rental agreement, or mortgage bill), immunization records and birth certificates for all students being registered. If you have questions, please contact Marcy Easterly at marcye@straffordschools.net or (417) 736-7000 ext. 1503.

post_text:
Earlier today, Governor Parson ordered all Missouri schools to stay closed for the remainder of the school year. Our district is sad to close our doors for the rest of the school year. However, we know we must do our part to help continue the fight against COVID-19.

We are communicating internally, and also with DESE and other state and federal officials, to get answers to all of the questions our staff, students, and community are asking. Please watch for more information to be shared next week as our administration finalizes many decisions.

In the meantime, we will continue providing our distance learning for all students until our last day of school, May 20. Our food program will also continue for the remainder of the school year. Stay well and safe!
shared_text:
Governor Mike Parson
April 9 at 2:56 PM ¬∑

We are ordering all Missouri public and charter schools to remain closed through the remainder of the academic year with the exceptions of nutrition services and child care that are outlined in our recent health order.

This recommendation was made by working together with the Missouri Department of Elementary and Secondary Education and several school superintendents from across the state -- from both urban and rural districts.

Schools should continue remote learning for their students until the end date previously set on their academic calendars.

post_text: Please read the updates to the ECC & Elementary materials pick-up now scheduled for Wednesday, March 25!
shared_text:
Strafford Elementary School
March 24 at 5:02 PM ¬∑

Strafford Elementary Families,

We miss you ALL and have been working hard to prepare materials and put plans in place to support our students. As you are probably aware, the Springfield-Greene County Health Department, Greene County, Christian County, and the City of Springfield have issued a ‚Äústay at home order‚Äù for our area starting on Thursday, March 26 and lasting 30 days.

With this new information we are moving up our distribution times for material pick-up. Early childhood and elementary packet pick-up and/or chromebooks can now be picked up from the elementary carline on Wednesday, March 25th from 4:00pm-8:00pm. Parents will stay in their car and staff will deliver the items to your car utilizing our pick-up and go system.

If you are unable to pick-up your student‚Äôs materials at this time and need to make arrangements for someone else to pick up, please email elementary@straffordschools.net. We appreciate your flexibility and are thinking of you all daily!

post_text:
Dear Strafford Staff and Families--

After much consideration and communication with the Springfield-Greene County Health Department and other area schools, Strafford R-VI Schools will be closed through Friday, April 3 in an effort to help isolate the spread of COVID-19. We do realize this has a major impact on many people. Our main focus at this time is protecting the safety and well being of our students, staff, and community.

Please read the press release with more details and information from our district website.

We realize that there will be many more questions to be answered. As this situation continues to evolve, we promise to share information and details once decisions are made.

Sincerely,

Brett Soden
Superintendent

post_text: Many of our SMS gifted students placed at the District 7 National History Day!
shared_text:
Strafford Middle School added a new photo to the album: 2019-20.
March 7 at 6:48 PM ¬∑

SMS does it again. These students competed at the District 7 National History Day competition held at MSU on Friday, March 6. From left to right: Taylor Landon placed third in Individual Exhibit, Colin Kugler placed first in Individual Performance, Oliver Bradley and Tyler Levell (not pictured Sophia Venosdel) placed fourth in Group Documentary, Amren King and Jackson Jacobson (not pictured Ryker Venosdel) took first place, for the third straight year, in Group Website. We are so proud of all the hard work and perseverance these students have shown preparing for this competition throughout this school year. We wish them luck as three of the project will now compete at the state competition at MU on April 25.

post_text: On February 19, 2020 the Lending Librarians Action Team from the elementary school presented their project at the Board of Education meeting. Action team leader and elementary librarian Melissa Morris brought 6 students from the team to represent the group. The students gave an overview of what the Little Free Library project is and described how the group works together to make decisions. Mrs. Morris gave recognition to the high school shop class that built the Little Free Library under the direction of Mr. Fabro. The mission statement for the Lending Librarians states they will do their part to make sure every person in the community and beyond has books in their hands and in their homes. The team expressed their excitement about having a place for the whole community to access free books year round.
